Describe the microbiome of the gut and compare to mouth and skin 

The human GI tract niche of a microbe is primarily determined by the microbe's requirements eg nutrients, aerobic/anaerobic, pH, etc and also the microbe's metabolic properties.  

 

 

 

Skin flora 

  • •Staphylococcus aureus  

  • •Staphylococcus epidermis  

  • •Proprionibacterium acnes 

  • •Corynebacteria spp 

  • •Proteobacteria 

 

Mouth flora 

-Veillonella are gram positive, anaerobic 

-Furospirochetes 

-Lactobacillus 

 

Microbial niches 

Specific structural niches such as crypts, the inner mucus layer, and the appendix may be crucial to facilitate immune homeostasis, to protect commensal species from competitors and to re-seed the gut microbiota after an environmental challenge.  

 

Some microbes are able to penetrate the inner mucus layer and enter crypt spaces. Environmental challenges such as diet perturbations, antibiotic consumption and abnormalities in GI motility alter the lumen community. However, the inner mucosal environment and crypts protect important bacterial species. These crypts and mucosa serve as reservoirs to repopulate the lumen after environmental challenges. 

 

Note: dysbiosis is an unhealthy change in the normal bacterial ecology of a part of a body, eg a loss of beneficial microbes, loss of diversity, or expansion of pathological microbes.  

 

Describe the immune defenses and vulnerability of the gut 

The gut-associated lymphoid tissue (GALT) has an enormous antigen load, with continual exposure to foreign matter. Hence, it is less responsive to foreign antigen.  

 

-Mechanical barrier: mucosal epithelial surface 

-Chemical barrier: saliva, lysozyme in mouth; acid in stomach; mucus, bile, anti-microbial enzymes (secretory IgA), lymphoid tissue in small intestine; mucus in large intestine 

-Commensal microflora in mouth, small intestine and large intestine  

 

Dietary antigens are largely absorbed by the end of the jejunum. Peyer's patches are found predominantly in the ileum. Commensal microbes also increase in load toward distal portions of the GI tract.  

 

Peyer's patches 

M-cells can act as a portal of entry for pathogens into the GALT. M cells lack micro-villi.  

 

CD8+ Cytotoxic Intraepithelial lymphocytes (IEL) 

IELs are mainly in the proximal small intestine, and are located in the mucosal epithelium to respond to antigenic stimulation. IEL cytotoxic T cells are less reactive than other CD8+ T cells, preventing indiscriminate inflammation.  

 

CD4+ T helper cells 

Th1 CD4+ T cells have a constant distribution in the lamina propria of the small and large intestines, protecting against viruses. Th17 CD4+ T cells are greatest in number in the lamina propria of the duodenum and jejunum to protect against extracellular bacteria and fungus.  

 

These cells are upregulated during damage, with dendritic cells activating them.  

 

FOX3+ T regulatory cells 

These have constant distribution in the lamina propria in the small intestine, and have even greater number in the large intestine. They dampen down the immune response, when dendritic cells sample food in the absence of damage and activate them.  

 

IgA plasma B cells 

These have constant distribution in the lamina propria of the small intestine, and have even greater number in the large intestine. Dimeric IgA molecules are secreted into the inner mucus to maintain correct populations of microflora.  

 

Note: pathobiont = commensal species that can lead to disease under certain specific conditions 

Symbiont = mutualistic or commensal species

Describe the mechanisms through which infection can result in vomiting and diarrhea 

Rotavirus 

The replicating virus damages water, salt and glucose transport channels. Too much fluid in the lumen results in dehydrating diarrhea. Infected epithelial cells are destroyed without inflammation or blood loss. CD8+ IELs sit in the mucosal epithelium. Large numbers of virus particles appear in the feces.  

 

Norovirus 

Virus invades and destroys upper villus epithelium, causing decreased Na+ and H2O uptake from intestinal lumen. Fever, nausea, vomiting and watery diarrhea result.  

 

Staph aureus 

Produces 5 different enterotoxins, each by a different strain. Vomiting occurs within 3-6 hours without diarrhea. Enterotoxins are heat stable and resistant to acid and stomach enzymes.  

 

Clostridium botulinum 

A, B and E toxins are ingested in food or produced in gut by the bacteria, absorbed into the blood which then blocks neurotransmission or peripheral nerves. Symptoms include flaccid paralysis, muscle weakness and respiratory arrest.  

 

Define probiotic and briefly describe their potential uses 

Probiotics are live microbes which when administered in adequate amounts confer a health benefit on the host. Probiotics perform the following: 

-Compete against pathogens for nutrients 

-Bind to adhesion sites, preventing pathogen attachment 

-Signaling to immune cells may result in secretion of cytokines to target pathogen for destruction 

-May attack pathogenic organisms directly by secreting certain toxins 

 

Probiotics are not effective against traveler's diarrhea or necrotizing enterocolitis, but are useful for the prevention of GI disease at all ages.  

 

Describe clinical features of the following: 

Staphylococcal food poisoning 

Bacteria; incubation 3-6 hours; symptoms: vomiting without diarrhea; transmission through cold food/left overs; mechanism: secretes enterotoxins with emetic properties 

 

Norovirus infection 

Virus; incubation 1/2 - 2 days; symptoms: fever, diarrhea, nausea, vomiting; transmission through fecal-oral; mechanism: kills epithelial cells to cause malabsorption (along with inflammation). Resolved 1-2 days.  

 

Rotavirus infection 

Virus; incubation 1 - 4 days; symptoms: vomiting and diarrhea; transmission through fecal-oral; mechanism: kills epithelial cells to cause malabsorption (along with inflammation). Resolved in 9 days. 

 

Invasive bacterial infection by salmonella 

Bacteria; incubation 8hrs - 3 days; symptoms: fever, diarrhea, nausea, vomiting, abdominal cramping; transmission through contaminated food or water; mechanism: exudative diarrhea for gastroenteritis. Lasts about a week. 

 

Infection by salmonella typhi: 

Bacteria; incubation 8-14 days; symptoms: fever, vomiting, diarrhea, abdominal pains (typhoid fever); transmission through contaminated food or water; mechanism: bacteria enters lymphatic system, secretes endotoxins acting on neural and vascular apparatus, causing vasodilation and increased permeability, hence shock.  

 

Invasive bacterial infection by campylobacter 

Bacteria; incubation 2-5 days; symptoms: fever, bloody diarrhea, nausea, vomiting, abdominal cramps; transmission through contaminated food or water; mechanism: exudative diarrhea, secretion of cytolethal distending toxin to hinder immune signaling. Resolves in less than a week. 

 

Infection with toxin producing organism eg E Coli 

Bacteria; incubation 3-4 days; symptoms: severe stomach cramps, bloody diarrhea, vomiting (Shiga-toxin producing); transmission through fecal-oral; mechanism: Shiga toxin inhibits protein synthesis and causes cell death, hence exudative diarrhea. Lasts about a week. 

 

Enterotoxigenic E coli: 

Leading cause of traveler's diarrhea; secretes enterotoxin causing secretory diarrhea. Symptoms: watery diarrhea, vomiting may not be present. Nausea, fever.
